[00:00] [scene:intro]
VISUAL: Creator in a dark room, lit by a screen.
AUDIO: 'How much do you rely on being online? What if it all goes down? Are you prepared? It was an unremarkable day. I was working away when it began with a power cut. This actually never happens, but I thought no biggie. I\'ll just check my'

[00:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'phone to see what\'s going on. But to my surprise, my iPhone also lost its mobile data. In fact, even the GSM didn\'t work. So, I couldn\'t place or receive any calls or messages. It\'s a weird feeling'

[00:27] [scene:context]
VISUAL: A news article headline about VPNs being banned.
AUDIO: 'to experience complete isolation in a world where information and connectivity are so uninterrupted. Then it\'s also the realization of just how much of everything I interact with happens'

[00:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'somewhere far away in a cloud or on a server. How much of my data is not here with me. Luckily, power came back within a few hours, but it made me wonder if perhaps I should be more prepared. Especially with modern geopolitics and'

[00:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'persistent degradation of services. This is where today\'s build comes in. First, assuming a cutoff, what am I missing and what do I actually want? Well, intelligence and insights. This will'

[01:04] [scene:concept]
VISUAL: Hand-drawn diagram showing "Intelligence & Insight," "Personal Vault," and "Communications" as core functions.
AUDIO: 'probably include some compute as well as banks of resources like annotated maps, medical wikis, survival guides, tools, maybe some local AI. I\'d like a personal vault. I want to be able to access my'

[01:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'files, memories, photos, maybe some music, books, and entertainment. I like some degree of communications. A looking glass as extensive as possible into the [music] external world to figure out'

[01:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'what\'s going on if disaster strikes and what to do about it. Now, since this is a kit and we\'re role-playing scenarios here, I thought of a few principles to underpin all of my subsequent choices. I want this to run completely offline'

[01:42] [scene:concept]
VISUAL: Hand-drawn diagram detailing kit principles: "Offline Forever," "Off-grid for 7 days," "Redundancy Built-in," "Cross-Compatibility," and "Mobile/Travel-Ready."
AUDIO: 'indefinitely and completely off-grid for at least a week. [music] I want some built-in redundancy by design to avoid critical single points of failure. Cross-compatibility [music] of items to boost resilience. And I want this to be'

[01:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'relatively mobile. I want to be able to pick it up and move it with me. With these constraints, [music] my idea was to start with what\'s both a primary enabler and limiting factor of the whole'

[02:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'design. This EcoFlow power station is really cool. Think of it as a sophisticated massive battery with all sorts of systems, [music] checks, and balances in place to operate at peak performance. It\'s got multiple'

[02:20] [scene:process]
VISUAL: Hand writing on paper, possibly sketching designs.
AUDIO: 'inputs to charge it, including fast charging from mains, DC, and even solar panels. These give us interesting possibilities for the build. [music] The power station can fuel devices of up to 3 kW, but that\'s not what we\'re going to'

[02:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'do. We\'re going to aim for a far more modest load to see us through an entire [music] week of usage. After some calculations based on the rated capacity of 2 kW hour, this ended up being around 30 W average draw. In fact, it wasn\'t'

[02:47] [scene:process]
VISUAL: Hands typing on a keyboard.
AUDIO: 'just a theoretical average I arrived at. Early on, I bootstrapped a bunch of loads out of stuff lying around, and then monitor the drop [music] over the next week with this actually useful companion app. And the math checked out.'

[03:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: '30 W average draw may not seem like much, but it\'s very workable. We were in business and cooking. So, I started researching fairly broadly about things that may fit our menu. I\'m not going to lie, this was a long journey. It wasn\'t'

[03:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'just a couple of days of research, it was rabbit hole [music] after rabbit hole of getting lost and progressively getting more and more excited. It was surprisingly fun and a privilege to discover so many dedicated [music] communities online and the awesome tools'

[03:26] [scene:hardware]
VISUAL: Unboxing a Wuben X1 Pro flashlight.
AUDIO: 'they use and build for energy efficiency and prudence. I prioritized passive cooling and low wattage [music] where I could. In some categories, this alone surfaced clear winners. Of course, I had to cut some corners. This won\'t be a'

[03:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'data center with disaster [music] recovery, a cell tower network, and an NSA outpost all-in-one, but I was getting glimpses at a surprisingly complete and robust set of capabilities. Once I identified and got the components'

[03:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'for the kit, I started the puzzle of configuring all of them into one coherent unit. &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; Nothing beats outlining things in real life, measuring and prototyping through. I know we have 3D scanners and Star Wars technology, but some things are best'

[04:06] [scene:hardware]
VISUAL: Unwrapping a large black box, likely the EcoFlow power station.
AUDIO: 'served simple. &gt;&gt; We\'re going to need a bigger printer. &gt;&gt; But with a bigger printer [music] come bigger problems, specifically weight and'

[04:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'space. Luckily, once it assumed its new position in my flat, this just worked beautifully straight away for me. So, I could move on to designing the case. And for this, I had a lot of fun ideas to'

[04:31] [scene:ui]
VISUAL: A PowerPoint slide showing radio communication codes and a diagram of HDD, ZM (ZimaBoard), and WiFi connections.
AUDIO: 'try out. It wasn\'t just going to protect my kit from the urban elements in my flat and the chaos in my study. I had higher aspirations. I wanted this to guide and enable [music] the kit\'s actual deployment. And also, something I'

[04:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'admire in industrial design, the case itself had to offer intuitive key information about the capabilities available and how to correctly use them. The best user manual is no user manual. The more I worked on this, the more'

[04:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'excited I got. Now, when it comes to printing on this scale, the complexity, filament, and time go up exponentially. Luckily, my years of experience paid off and I got this assembly working first'

[05:09] [scene:hardware]
VISUAL: 3D printed parts for the case laid out on a desk.
AUDIO: 'try. It actually took me ages to get this right. Not just because of sizing, but also the logical layout, writing up the'

[05:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'clear UI, cutting [music] this into simple geometry to avoid supports, getting the clasps to snap [music] in a satisfying way, moderating for gravity, and some other refinements. And then, after what felt like another century of'

[05:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'printing, I finally had it. &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; This is ATU version [music] 1, a'

[05:51] [scene:hardware]
VISUAL: Close-up of the Portapack H4M screen displaying map view with altitude, latitude, longitude, and speed.
AUDIO: 'decentralized tech stack, offline and off-grid. It\'s intuitive, [music] durable, low power, and low maintenance. It features redundancy by design [music] and modularity. Locally I knowledge repositories, personal vault storage,'

[06:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'whole earth navigation, [music] computation, communication, and monitoring. Okay, this was really fun. I put together a write-up for you below, but'

[06:16] [scene:hardware]
VISUAL: Close-up of cables and components neatly arranged inside the custom case.
AUDIO: 'let me quickly show you some of the cool things this can do. The case is less than 1 kg of filament made of very simple symmetrical shapes. M3 bolts reinforce the hinges and it comes apart cleanly all the way. I love how this'

[06:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'turned out. On the bottom of the case, everything is neatly laid out with just enough space and finger slots to make retrieval a breeze. Underneath the devices, there\'s a compartment for accessories and cables. I hate when you'

[06:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'have to dig for extras and this eliminates that problem. It\'s all in one place. You may have noticed there\'s a lot going on with the top of the case. I designed it as an integral part of the'

[06:54] [scene:ui]
VISUAL: ZimaBoard's app store interface showing applications like Home Assistant, Jellyfin, Syncthing, Nextcloud, and Open WebUI.
AUDIO: 'kit. These slots enable the deployment of a fully functional home server. The brain of this is a Zimaboard 2 with its super efficient passively cooled chipset which keeps us well within our power'

[07:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'limits. It\'s got PCIE expansion options and SATA connectivity into our main storage drive. Zimaboard offers a Linux base server OS that\'s easy to use. Deploying applications is very intuitive either from their templates or your'

[07:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'bespoke Docker instruction sets. I actually use both for mine. The community is so vibrant around self-hosting and there are lots of options you can pick from. I\'ll show you five I like the most. Image synchronizes'

[07:31] [scene:ui]
VISUAL: Jellyfin media server interface displaying a collection of movies.
AUDIO: 'with your phone and delivers Google Photos style search organization and sharing for your memories without any third parties involved. Paperless NGX is a document management system featuring a full searchable local digital archive'

[07:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'with automatic scanning, tagging, and organizing. Jellyfin is a media server that gathers films, series, and music into a personal streaming library that you control without any subscriptions or'

[07:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'tracking. Kiwix serves Wikipedia and other vast knowledge collections offline to any device making the world\'s information instantly searchable without an internet connection. Open WebUI is a self-hosted interface that turns local'

[08:09] [scene:ui]
VISUAL: A phone screen showing "ZimaBoard2" and its IP address, indicating connection to the ZimaBoard.
AUDIO: 'or remote LLMs into a clean ChatGPT-style workspace with conversations, tools, and workflows. You can use these apps and more locally just like any other service. The only'

[08:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'difference being that you control everything and you own your data. This rugged AGM phone actually pairs extremely well with a server. Zim OS is fully compatible with Android and you\'ve got apps or web apps for all of the'

[08:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'services we\'re running. But there\'s more that earned this phone a place because it\'s Android, you can load up loads of software on it including some of its own local AI, offline maps, and knowledge repositories. It\'s got a bright large'

[08:46] [scene:hardware]
VISUAL: Close-up of a Heltec LoRa device screen showing Meshtastic interface with message count, nodes online, and LoRa frequency.
AUDIO: 'display easy to see outdoors, a loud speaker, a big light in case of emergencies that you can access via a physical button, a massive battery, and probably my favorite feature, this lovely integrated thermal camera. And in'

[08:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'case you need to communicate in a decentralized way, the phone can link up with these lower devices which give you about 10 km worth of range without relying on any cell towers or any external infrastructure. And there\'s'

[09:13] [scene:ui]
VISUAL: Portapack H4M screen showing a menu of receive options including ADS-B, Audio, Radiosonde, Weather, Radio, Scanner.
AUDIO: 'another cool thing about these in particular. They can be used standalone and come with an interface for sensors so you can gather data remotely on your very own network for emergency monitoring in the event of a blackout. I'

[09:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'picked up this. The H4M is a standalone software-defined radio. It\'s a true Swiss Army knife and it basically allows you to see pretty much everything transmitted. Wi-Fi, Bluetooth,'

[09:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'sub-gigahertz signals, but also FM and AM radio, ADSB for planes, weather satellites, amateur radio signals, weather stations, and so much more. For example, I could listen into the London'

[09:49] [scene:hardware]
VISUAL: Close-up of the Wuben X1 Pro flashlight being held, showing its power indicator.
AUDIO: 'Heathrow Airport control tower communications from my flat. To make things easier to operate, I have laid out the most important frequencies right here on the box. Also on the box is the Morse alphabet and some useful codes. In'

[10:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'an emergency, laws permitting, you can radio Morse out, of course, but you can also use sound or even light. This Woobur X1 Pro is incredibly tough and extremely bright. The throw is up to'

[10:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'half a kilometer. It has SOS built into it. And another useful trick for us, it can charge other devices from its own USB-C reserve. This contributes to redundancy, which is something I saw'

[10:26] [scene:text]
VISUAL: A document showing "Solar energy scenario" with harvest rates (Wh/day) for different weather conditions.
AUDIO: 'across the kit. But how do you keep track of these capabilities overlaps in case of failures? Well, this is also laid out on the case itself. Here you also have tables to estimate power reserve at different configurations of'

[10:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'the kit. And I\'m happy to say we actually achieved our original 7 days. Even more impressive is when you factor in solar harvest. With a worst-scenario of bad winter European days, some'

[10:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'configurations of this kit can run indefinitely. This is so cool given how much it can give you. With a power station and solar panels, you can basically run your personal internet and communications network off-grid and'

